History of IBM: From cheese slices to flights in the cosmos.
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago and initially had the complicated name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history was linked to the year 80 of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 presided over the Society's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him lead the company.
The leader then made the company's founder a shadow - it is on Watson's ideas that the identity and culture of society have so far been based.
Watson led the Kusqu' firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machinery for business and trade - from cheese and meat slicers to register boxes.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, the turnover increased to as much as $9 million and began the expansion of the firm in all parts of the world.
Watson was for the firm so irreplaceable that after 40 years of management, his son occupied the chair of director Thomas Watson Junior.
Under its leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s people and computers at IBM helped NASA to guide flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
In the meantime in 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determines the computer standard of the time with the name of IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but purchased Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with advice and services with high added value.
