How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time proposed travel mainly in the socialist bloc countries, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for the holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a inclination for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, in Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the west, however, it was necessary to tail all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it had not yet been won.
The currency agreement that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where therefore there were many country houses and chalets that the Czechs were buying and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989 Czech travel has been a major revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at most, the Czechs spent 4 million vacations last year abroad in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are unaware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 as part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90s of the last century in neighbouring western countries has caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel for a long time by aircraft to the west that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example, in Paris travel organizations put Czechs to sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to take with itself his own food canned, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was the exchangeability of the Czech krona, which finally allowed our tourists after decades of free purchasing power from the Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have increased which has led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to an increasing demand for travel travel agencies began in 1997 to prepare tours with air charter links which through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what was previously.
At the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free links with virtually most developed countries around the world except the EUs that later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year and every year direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU deleted visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the group of developed countries.
In 2008, Czechs also spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history they spent more than 15,000 krona per person for vacation abroad, including the related charges.
