According to the report on the allocations by frosts from the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there have been damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remainder of 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main affected crops were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity has led to a steady increase in State unemployment, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of State unemployment during the first three quarters of the year has been seen, since from January to March 55 thousand 053 signalees were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate has become 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average has continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, an increase of more than 74 thousand unemployed signalees, an increase from the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multi-factorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly by actions carried out by public policy.
"What is observed is an increase in unemployment which is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money-laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work to earn, invest and use them in something," he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because they already have a lot of difficulty to find work, these people remain here and ask for sources of work, which makes unemployment increase," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the signal labour market is worsening in view of the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates among the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state is working there without contributing as a worker in any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of seriousness, another reason for discontinuing the state is the low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of signal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
IED Contraction
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, in 2011, the highest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment over the past 10 years was recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June, the State FDI reached $630 thousand,697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to the $5,143 thousand,312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, recorded mainly by the tertiary sector companies.
The debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the Government of the State in July requested approval of a 3-billion-weight credit for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600-billion-weighted and no debt in any sector of the State economy was observed until November.
Reactions
For representatives of the employers sector, the first year of Government of Mario López Valdés demonstrated a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of the Sinaloa economy during this year was really very poor, we must work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have to align the effort of everyone and above all the good already synchronized progress of this new government team, hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as frosts from the beginning of the year retained the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is produced by several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that doesn't turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows for an acceptable level of flow in trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year, we close much below the expectations we had," he says.
Redefine the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patron Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa, said that we want to channel the state to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the State, because it is important to detonate the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a vision for the future that better channel the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to achieve good results in different areas of economic development, there are some progress, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in the management of public policy.
"There are some things that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, which I can say is that much work has been done and the Government is aware of the fact that there is still much to do," he said.
