"They must make a contribution of 12 million and despite the fact that the year will soon end they have given us nothing, even if since July they had to give us a share," he says, "and we, in order not to record delays, we have started the works and we have made a lot of progress, but we need money."
He mentioned that last year, during the administration of Jesús Aguilar Padilla, the State had not paid the corresponding contributions, so at the beginning of the administration the Municipality had to apply for a credit to cover the 7 million that the administration of the State had not provided on that occasion.
"We had already experienced this in the previous six-year period because the State had not had the economic capacity to participate and the programs continue to function, and this year we, in order to access these programs, had to obtain the resources to cover what the State had not paid," he said.
Despite the fact that there is a commitment from the State authorities to provide these resources, he stated that they had applied to the Secretary of Administration and Finance, Armando Villarreal, to activate management to ensure that the corresponding percentages arrive as quickly as possible.
"They must provide almost 12 million and despite the fact that the year will soon end, they have given us nothing."
The Court valid "the analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analogue signals by digital means is one of the most important changes that the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has raised the constitutional controversy that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue coupura" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes needed to invalidate it have not been held.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his responsibilities when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was halted for not having reached the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation on radio and television is a statutory assignment to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and statutory reserve.
In favour of the project only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies in order to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions provided by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of the Ministers also resolved to lift the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project of which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for public administration to prepare for it.
"I also consider that the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected if it were done," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate of state management.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years, and this results in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To adjourn the change, he said, would adjourn the benefits of digitisation which involves a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "requires the operation of a whole system to establish, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, a group of powers which the Constitution grants to the power of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries from all over the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite having the highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has somehow invaded the sphere of competences of Congress, as it assures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislature, he assures.
The possibility of a vote-by-vote account in Michoacán is analysed.
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of "voting by vote" is a reality with regard to the election trial this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Pre-Trial Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), María de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards in the federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán did not approve either his Political Constitution or his Electoral Code of State or the Electoral Justice Act, at the same time as the Congress of the State approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral trial to enter into force, and Governor Lionel Godoy Rangel omitted his publication within the time limits provided for in the Act of the Official Journal of the State, arguing that he had some objections.
On the same November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and described as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the State's representative for constitutional reforms, since it does not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Angeles Llanderal stated that through the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the IEM General Council, it will be possible to achieve the partial and total counting of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of voting and counting in the ballot file is not in the Chair of the ballot; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total counting of votes received in all polls of the election may be achieved when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged candidate who wins the respective election and the one who obtained the second place in the poll is equal to or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the party representative and/or coalition that presented the second of the candidates indicated.
The total polling may also take place if at the end of the joint counting it follows that the difference between the alleged successful candidate and that of the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the political party representative whose second date the candidate was released, in which case the electoral packages that were the subject of the partial counting will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
