The new Italian government will be formed Wednesday
Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the brink of the economic disaster.
The Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of the economic disaster and put the whole Eurozone at risk.
A communiqué from the Presidential Palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in his majority by technocrats, even if it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the outcome of his discussions with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner to journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
The "framework is now well drawn", he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a time shorter than usual, while Italy fights a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to levels that are impossible to support.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By stressing the pressure on Monti to move forward, the instability of the markets to place the yield of the Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, to which the crisis forced him to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good outcome," said Angelino Alfano, Secretary of the Center-Right Party.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the Government of the technocratic majority that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new government in Monti must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or delay in its efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations.
He'll finish his round of meetings Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels between the uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.9 billion, would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should continue until the forthcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the generalized predictions that politicians would only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections proceed.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his office, but the big parties insist that it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process that is forced by financial pressure.
Political sources reported that mutual mistrust and party disagreement complicate the attempt to include political figures.
