Quinteto included the country in its turn to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said that the group is ready to offer one of its best concerts next Sunday on the National Stadium.
They have waited for more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also become a dream to happen in that country.
It was the bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, speaking exclusively with Viva from Brazil last week.
The group is located in the South American wing of its two decades of work celebration tour and on Sunday 20 will make its only stop in Central America.
That day will be on the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., next to the Los Angeles Group The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the complete transcription of which is found in La Nación on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will happen in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America, and so far this has been great.
I spent only once on vacation in Costa Rica; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So we're excited to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is some kind of devotion to the group, fans live with intensity the previous days.
What is your message for your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and sorry for the fact that so much time had to go to this concert.
Some people already say his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a little pressure to your visit.
Some of the biggest shows we've had in the last 21 years have been held in the last two weeks.
We have offered a two giant shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that this has brought us into shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing it.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places for surfing; this is how we learned it, through the people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you've offered huge shows, with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never been there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the directory.
What's that supposed to be?
I think it's partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, that's why it's very difficult to choose which songs to play every evening.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't interpreted for a long time, it helps us to stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved these songs and that we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting to us and therefore I think it becomes more interesting to people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I think that none of us had imagined that we were going to form a large rock band, and the fact that we did it for over 20 years made it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell about our blessings and we are deeply moved by the fact that we can continue to make music together.
We love each other and we love to create music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world to which we have always wanted to go.
Things could not be better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of major groups.
We are very friendly with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group comes from a city, but it's far more strange when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honor for us to be part of the Seattle Group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we participated in a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to be still friends with all of them and it's an honor for us to be part of this Seattle sound that popped up.
It's also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us were together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many groups normally last.
Firstly, I believe that we are all lucky to be still alive and, secondly, we are all concerned about the others.
We are all intimate friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone freedom to experience.
We have confidence in each other with each other's music and it could not go better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don't spend too much time on tour because it's easy to fall into this game of great crowds and people who love your music.
If we don't forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we must respect music and what brought it, without thinking about the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which doesn't really matter to any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote good songs and at first it was great.
