MSS announces protocol to find the gene of obesity
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the 'Genetic Protocol on Obesity of Children and Adolescents', which will allow them to have markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the National Medical Centre of the 20th century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by third-cycle specialists and students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) from the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The survey invites the population with or without rights to participate, to attend the IMSS sports units in Valle de México, where evidence is made to minors every Saturday starting at 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Unit Sportive Cuauhtémoc (State of West Mexico) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Unit Sportive Nezahualcóyolt (State of East Mexico).
After achieving the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Unit Independence (south of Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this research and that it is aware of the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of inherited diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
It detailed that Saturdays will be applied to all participants of anthropometric measurements (weight, size, size circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (required to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years, in the case of boys, there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity and in the case of girls of 47 per cent; in the case of overweight, there was also a dramatic increase', emphasized the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for searching markers is based on the fact that the country's population is different from the other by its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent of Indo-American inheritance, 30 per cent European and five per cent African inheritance, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that obesity genetics generally result in the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full assessment of children, which allows to detect if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms indicate the likelihood of metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential way, doctors send it in writing to parents, each explaining the measures and changes in the lifestyle they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the largest consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates of carbon (tamales - meat pasta of corn flour wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and the genetic analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid the cases
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signs that the pavement was solved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cases each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the cases could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on the cases, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the performance, and therefore, the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, adds it.
This means that in the streets asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he said, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass it by generating efforts, it allows forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he said, one puts a final layer called the bearing layer, made of fine stone, i.e., sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
Since it is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the layer of asphalt and provide adhesion in the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the bearing layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassis.
In the case of the formation of a case, he said, the first one that gets wasted is the rolling film and only subsequently is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The Member of the National Research System explained that vehicle load is another important factor in case formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent case formation.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still much to be done to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair the cases easily and without having to use high temperatures.
