The members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to enter again, through a court order, in Manhattan, where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another Great Apple Park.
Hundreds of protesters flocked in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access through a court order that allowed the 'indignados' to camp again in this place, while the other side of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new arrests.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the place, we will settle in another place and continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations," says one of the spokespersons of the "Occupy Wall Street" movement, Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the response of the "indignities" to the evacuation of their camp, personally dictated by the Mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, came to the courts, where Justice Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the camp and allowing protesters to remain in the camp.
In addition, the 'indignados' occupied a new park at the confluence of Canal Street and the Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland tunnel, which united New York and New Jersey, owned by the Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and stopped some demonstrators, even though Bray could not confirm the actual figure, ensuring that he had seen some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization assures that there are hundreds of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved in support of the members of the movement and tried to intervene in favour of them before the Police.
