Some demonstrators so far carried and distributed copies of this judicial order at that time and even handed it over to the officers who monitored the place, which caused 'some small clashes', said Bray, who denounced the fact that some officials had hit the demonstrators.
The judicial order prohibits the authorities from evacuating the members of Occupy Wall Street or from applying 'laws published after the beginning of the occupation or from prohibiting demonstrators from returning to the park with tents or other properties they used before'.
Mayor Bloomberg pointed out in front of the press that because of this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and to demonstrators, to whom, however, he warned that local laws do not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The city councillor personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn at Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the demonstrators 'violated the law'.
Bloomberg explained that he had ordered to evacuate because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate laws and in some cases, to harm other people," because "some stores had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"This morning's evacuation at dawn has been repulsive and demonstrates that Bloomberg is more interested in defending financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman for the movement, who accused the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression".
The Occupy Wall Street officials also indicated that they do not think of organizing "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on September 17.
