Japan surrendered after the earthquake
GDP increases by 1.5% through domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, convalescent again after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in Japan since World War II.
The Government of Tokyo's first estimates calculated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have diminished.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to turn the page permanently: GDP increased 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at annualized rates.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1 per cent, compared to the decrease of 0.9 per cent of the capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decrease after six months of unabated increase.
However, the real incentive of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Kenyan impulse that invites to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructure, to use the shortcomings for zero cross.
Japan has woken up mainly as a result of the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travels and entertainment activities.
