It is necessary to legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, said a committee of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the Royal Society of Canada report
With regard to palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians accept to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to that end.
This is one of the conclusions of an imposing report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts have participated in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code so as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to a patient who is deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the start of the game, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the planet.
If Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, we are told by experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the wish most Canadians have to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, in Quebec, this rate is the highest, with 86% of deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that are contrary to the federal government's position, which has already said that they want nothing to change to the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, which have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that such decriminalization leads to abuse in application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on non-competent or unconsenting persons.
On the contrary, he claimed yesterday in teleconference Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, there would be more cases of these overflows precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favor of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of life to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of older or disabled people are less valuable.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, the pollers estimate that 41% should not be prosecuted.
With regard to the maintenance or cessation of care with a patient, the situation is less clear, says the authors of the report.
Therefore, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it is indicated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Committee of Experts also requests that health professionals be trained to respect a refusal of end-of-life care without fear of criminal prosecution.
With regard to palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Finally, in terms of palliative or terminal sedation, already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee requests that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and that it is subject to the same procedures.
Reserves from other experts
Some health law experts have already made reservations about the findings of the report of the Royal Society of Canada experts.
Mr Pierre Deschamps, a health law specialist, described as "extreme" the position of the experts signing the report, among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to patients in terminal phase.
