This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is perhaps electorally paid; but it is very expensive economically.
As noted by economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting anemic immigration to growth and a loss of employment.
The concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may replace national workers, especially those who are underqualified, with lower pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, most of whom work in sectors with a shortage of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most qualified in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow job supply.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthetics, these complementaritys between nationals and migrants make immigrants' arrivals have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% of real long-term wages.
