The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe to Russia through the Baltic Sea, entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with splendour.
Over 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new pipeline that directly links Russia under the sea to Germany.
The German chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte played together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe through a first 1.224 km tube connecting the Saint Petersburg region to the Mecklenburg-Pomerania Land.
A second tube is due to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be delivered, i.e. equivalent to all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has airs of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic States.
The North Stream will make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose a bit of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is to say whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the price of a weakening energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to succeed in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us organically," confirmed François Fillon by opening this pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical operation.
The submarine tube is made of concrete steel to protect it from ship anchorages.
It is based on the seabed, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines dating from World War II.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, by precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for the Northern Stream company.
Measures to protect fauna and flora also had to be multiplied.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts on its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was provided for outside Sweden, but the project managers gave up while the Swedishs were reluctant to see a Russian state company standing permanently off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop passing the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leak, therefore, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned welding to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline shall be carried out by an underwater robot, driven by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft circulating within the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide of a meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, it provides accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to be repaired.
The flow of gas is simply assured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the beginning, and 100 on the arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) and the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have established a joint venture, known as Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company, for 20 renewable years, all gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their expenses, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that happens, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand card.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give the taste of writing.
He has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskin Book is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
Yet, the Moleskine Book as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decides to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The book is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin (taupe skin) which means a varnished cotton used to cover banquets, for example.
This type of book was highly appreciated by writers and travellers.
" Moleskine gave to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of the avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has become responsible for the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins.
We are far from the confidential production of the first few years, where only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine exceeds the Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a portrait-robot of the buyer, as the notebook of notes seduces both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, with 12 employees at its beginning, accounts for almost 100 today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in the bookstores, from the Fnac to the small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour " where architects or artists exhibit their own book.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendar, pens, computer covers... The brand is spread over a wide range of media.
A success that has made a huge difference: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was redeemed by the SG Capital Europe investment fund, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskin's history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of people with disabilities is opening today.
Despite a voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the whole population.
Discouragement?
"No, he points out Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled."
" The progress made over the last 15 years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
" Nevertheless, there is still a great deal to be done. "
It has to be said that for the disabled, there are still many obstacles before accessing employment.
They are rather older: 37% are older than 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that particularly complicate the return to employment, and which "constitute the knot of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
This is for objective brakes.
It remains the unspoken, the attitudes that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepriser Association for the City indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, show a 2.6% ratio.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Managing Director of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
" The Act of 2005, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc. "
"But this improvement also translates true awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of the establishments of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises of 100 to 199 employees.
